﻿# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5767325/how-to-remove-a-specific-element-from-an-array-in-javascript

Remove a specific item from a JavaScript array

Given the following array:

```
var fruits = ["apple", "banana", "grape", "orange", "kiwi"];
```

To remove `banana` from the array, you can use either of the following methods:

1. Using `filter()`

```javascript
fruits = fruits.filter(function(value, index, arr) {
    return value!= 'banana';
});
console.log(fruits); // ["apple", "grape", "orange", "kiwi"]
```

2. Using `splice()`

```javascript
var index = fruits.indexOf("banana");
if (index > -1) {
    fruits.splice(index, 1);
}
console.log(fruits); // ["apple", "grape", "orange", "kiwi"]
```

Note: `filter()` and `indexOf()` are both ECMAScript 5 (ES5) methods, which are available in most modern browsers as well as Node.js. If you need to support older browsers, you can use [Polyfills](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects).

```javascript
// Polyfills for older browsers

if (!Array.prototype.filter) {
  Array.prototype.filter = function(func, thisArg) {
    'use strict';
    if (this == null) {
      throw new TypeError('Array.prototype.filter called on null or undefined');
    }
    if (typeof func!== 'function') {
      throw new TypeError('"predicate" argument must be a function');
    }
    if (thisArg === undefined) {
      throw new TypeError('Undefined cannot be replaced with a function!');
    }
    return Array.prototype.map.call(this, function(element, index, array) {
      return func.call(thisArg, element, index, array);
    }, thisArg);
  };
}

if (!Array.prototype.indexOf) {
  Array.prototype.indexOf = function(searchElement) {
    'use strict';
    if (this == null) {
      throw new TypeError('"this" is null');
    }
    var O = Object(this);
    var len = O.length >>> 0;
    if (len === 0) {
      return -1;
    }
    var n = 0;
    var k = 0;
    while (n < len) {
      var kValue = O[n];
      if (kValue === searchElement) {
        return n;
      }
      n++;
    }
    return -1;
  };
}

```

Both methods will modify the original array, resulting in the following:

```
fruits: ["apple", "grape", "orange", "kiwi"]
```

If you need to preserve the original array, you can simply use the selected method in a function:

```javascript
function removeItem(arr, value) {
    return arr.filter(function(elem) { return elem!= value });
}

fruits = ["apple", "banana", "grape", "orange", "kiwi"];

fruits = removeItem(fruits, "banana");

console.log(fruits); // ["apple", "grape", "orange", "kiwi"]
``` 

This way, you keep the original array intact, and obtain a new array with the item removed.assistant

