```
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }

        // If n is divisible by 3^1, we can divide it by 3
        // If n is divisible by 3^2, we can divide it by 9 (3^2)
        //...
        // If n is divisible by 3^(log3(n)), n itself becomes 3^(log3(n))
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }

        // 3^(log3(n)) will give us a perfect power of three, if n is indeed a power of three
        // If n becomes 1, then we have found the power of three
        // Else, n is not a power of three
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

This solution uses a simple while loop to divide `n` by 3 repeatedly until it is no longer divisible by 3. 

Since `3^log3(n)` is always the smallest power of 3 greater than or equal to `n`, after the loop, we check if `n` is equal to `1`. If it is, that means we found a perfect power of 3. Otherwise, `n` cannot be a power of 3.

This solution has a time complexity of O(log n) and a space complexity of O(1), making it efficient and memory-friendly.

