In this example, there are integers and strings in the input arrays. However, since we are not modifying the input arrays, we must convert all values to a common data type before finding the common elements. We can use PHP's `array_map()` function to convert all values to strings.

Modified function:

```php
function findCommonElements(array...$arrays) {

  $result = array();

  // The first array will be used for comparison
  $compareArray = $arrays[0];

  // Convert all values to strings
  $compareArray = array_map('strval', $compareArray);

  // Looping through the first array
  foreach ($compareArray as $value) {

    // Checking the value's presence in all subsequent arrays
    $allPresent = true;
    for ($i = 1; $i < count($arrays); $i++) {

      $arr = $arrays[$i];
      $arr = array_map('strval', $arr); // Convert to strings

      if (!in_array($value, $arr)) {
        $allPresent = false;
        break;
      }
    }

    // If found in all arrays, add it to the result array
    if ($allPresent) {
      $result[] = $value;
    }
  }

  // Return the result array
  return $result;
}
```

Now the `findCommonElements()` function handles arrays with different data types properly without modifying the arrays.
